00:04:00.420 --> 00:04:06.260
So just why is the refugee
question so urgent today?

00:04:06.260 --> 00:04:10.260
Displacement, after all,
is an ageless problem.

00:04:10.260 --> 00:04:12.990
One of the world's most
ancient written stories

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:16.149
is about exiles journeying
through the desert for 40

00:04:16.149 --> 00:04:19.959
years, and numerous oral
traditions similarly

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:25.570
locate their society's origins
in banishment and wandering.

00:04:25.570 --> 00:04:28.970
The refugee crisis of the
20th and 21st centuries,

00:04:28.970 --> 00:04:34.150
however, are truly something
new and different under the sun.

00:04:34.150 --> 00:04:37.590
Our modern category
of refugee status

00:04:37.590 --> 00:04:40.030
only emerged with the
rise of the nation

00:04:40.030 --> 00:04:42.960
state, which by
definition created

00:04:42.960 --> 00:04:46.150
its opposite statelessness.

00:04:46.150 --> 00:04:48.790
The first people to
be uprooted by war

00:04:48.790 --> 00:04:52.280
and identified as refugees
with a claim on the conscience

00:04:52.280 --> 00:04:56.900
of the world were Belgians
in World War I. Sadly,

00:04:56.900 --> 00:05:00.480
not many years later, even
more massive numbers of people

00:05:00.480 --> 00:05:03.430
were displaced by World
War II, heightening

00:05:03.430 --> 00:05:07.040
worldwide sensitivity to the
need for systematic refugee

00:05:07.040 --> 00:05:10.060
relief, and inspiring
the United Nations

00:05:10.060 --> 00:05:14.700
to issue the Declaration
of Human Rights in 1948.

00:05:14.700 --> 00:05:19.350
But official coordinated relief
operations took two more years

00:05:19.350 --> 00:05:20.720
to materialize.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:23.600
The United Nations High
Commission for Refugees,

00:05:23.600 --> 00:05:27.930
the UNHCR, was
established in 1950.

00:05:27.930 --> 00:05:32.080
The first emergency that
the UNHCR responded to

00:05:32.080 --> 00:05:35.840
was the Hungarian
uprising of 1956,

00:05:35.840 --> 00:05:38.790
an event within the
lifetime and memory of some

00:05:38.790 --> 00:05:40.740
of the people in this room.

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:44.860
Today, there are more
than 65 million forcibly

00:05:44.860 --> 00:05:47.260
displaced people worldwide.

00:05:47.260 --> 00:05:52.190
Nearly 34,000 people flee
their homes each day.

00:05:52.190 --> 00:05:55.330
Most of them seek
refuge somewhere

00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:58.110
in Africa or the Middle East.

00:05:58.110 --> 00:06:03.830
Fewer than 20% enter
Europe or the Americas.

00:06:03.830 --> 00:06:06.470
About 80% of the
world's refugees

00:06:06.470 --> 00:06:08.450
are women and children.

00:06:08.450 --> 00:06:11.130
Let's look closely
at one example

00:06:11.130 --> 00:06:13.930
for a better sense of
exactly what displacement

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:15.490
means for them.

00:06:15.490 --> 00:06:18.230
Drought and war in
Somalia robbed a woman

00:06:18.230 --> 00:06:21.260
named Isha and her family
of the livestock that

00:06:21.260 --> 00:06:23.470
had once made them prosperous.

00:06:23.470 --> 00:06:27.510
When they had nothing left,
Isha and her five young children

00:06:27.510 --> 00:06:30.140
walked through the
desert to Dadaab,

00:06:30.140 --> 00:06:33.250
62 miles inside
the Kenyan border.

00:06:33.250 --> 00:06:36.350
By the time they arrived, the
skin of the children's feet

00:06:36.350 --> 00:06:39.140
had been entirely worn away.

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:45.110
Dadaab opened in 1991 as a
temporary camp for the 90,000

00:06:45.110 --> 00:06:49.400
Somalis that the UN estimated
would be uprooted by warfare

00:06:49.400 --> 00:06:51.180
in their home country.

00:06:51.180 --> 00:06:56.480
Today, Dadaab houses nearly half
a million people-- Sudanese,

00:06:56.480 --> 00:06:59.010
Ethiopians, Congolese,
and Ugandans,

00:06:59.010 --> 00:07:02.930
as well as Somalis-- making
it the third largest city

00:07:02.930 --> 00:07:05.200
population-wise in Kenya.

00:07:05.200 --> 00:07:09.700
It has schools, hospitals,
and a commercial economy.

00:07:09.700 --> 00:07:12.700
But camps themselves
are problematic.

00:07:12.700 --> 00:07:15.660
Infectious disease,
supply shortages,

00:07:15.660 --> 00:07:18.800
and gender-based
violence run rampant.

00:07:18.800 --> 00:07:22.670
Camps also require toleration
by their host countries,

00:07:22.670 --> 00:07:25.880
and that tolerance
may not last forever.

00:07:25.880 --> 00:07:28.740
The Kenyan government, in
fact, has announced plans

00:07:28.740 --> 00:07:30.710
to close Dadaab.

00:07:30.710 --> 00:07:33.460
The current president of the
International Rescue Commission

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:36.380
recommends that
camps be replaced

00:07:36.380 --> 00:07:39.120
with greater support
to host countries

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:43.620
to integrate newcomers into the
mainstream of their societies.

00:07:43.620 --> 00:07:47.690
Yet recent events in Europe, not
to mention our own government's

00:07:47.690 --> 00:07:50.970
response to migrants
crossing our southern border,

00:07:50.970 --> 00:07:56.350
show that hopes for a warmer
welcome may not be realistic.

00:07:56.350 --> 00:07:59.550
The most pressing refugee
crisis in recent months

00:07:59.550 --> 00:08:03.940
