00:14:20.850 --> 00:14:24.780
who is a health program manager
from Save the Children's Syria

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:25.330
response.

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:27.232
He's actually from--
I presume he's

00:14:27.232 --> 00:14:28.940
from Aleppo, because
he got his education

00:14:28.940 --> 00:14:31.150
at the University of Aleppo.

00:14:31.150 --> 00:14:35.140
And he is now based in
Turkey, but obviously makes

00:14:35.140 --> 00:14:38.910
frequent trips to
Syria, and is involved

00:14:38.910 --> 00:14:42.610
in a set of critical
campaigns, including campaigns

00:14:42.610 --> 00:14:45.710
to ensure that a higher
proportion than is

00:14:45.710 --> 00:14:49.160
the case right now of Syrian
children are immunized.

00:14:49.160 --> 00:14:52.420
Some of you may be aware that
this drop in vaccination rates

00:14:52.420 --> 00:14:54.540
has been one of the
most concerning health

00:14:54.540 --> 00:14:56.360
correlates of the conflict.

00:14:56.360 --> 00:14:58.290
So thank you for joining us.

00:14:58.290 --> 00:15:00.270
And finally, last but
certainly not least,

00:15:00.270 --> 00:15:03.440
Rania Matar, our
independent photographer,

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:08.000
who was born and
raised in Lebanon,

00:15:08.000 --> 00:15:11.670
and is an architect by
training, but is now

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:15.440
a full-time
photographer, and also

00:15:15.440 --> 00:15:18.720
a teacher at the Massachusetts
College of Art and Design.

00:15:18.720 --> 00:15:24.330
She has a very long list
of credits to her name

00:15:24.330 --> 00:15:27.040
of exhibitions that her
work has been involved in,

00:15:27.040 --> 00:15:29.850
including, some of you may
have seen here at the MFA,

00:15:29.850 --> 00:15:33.100
the exhibition on
women from Iran,

00:15:33.100 --> 00:15:37.000
and other exhibitions
dealing with Arab women.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:40.430
She is currently part
of an exhibition called

00:15:40.430 --> 00:15:43.550
"Aftermath-- The Fallout of
War-- America in the Middle

00:15:43.550 --> 00:15:45.665
East", curated by
Carol McCusker.

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:51.340
She's clearly been recognized
for much of the work

00:15:51.340 --> 00:15:54.610
she's done, including
receiving the 2011 Legacy

00:15:54.610 --> 00:15:58.110
Award at the Griffin
Museum of Photography

00:15:58.110 --> 00:16:00.970
for the photographic
work she's done.

00:16:00.970 --> 00:16:03.060
So thank you all so
much for joining us,

00:16:03.060 --> 00:16:05.490
and perhaps you can all
come up and sit next to me

00:16:05.490 --> 00:16:06.410
on the panel.

00:16:06.410 --> 00:16:08.905
[APPLAUSE]

00:16:22.400 --> 00:16:23.220
-Good afternoon.

00:16:23.220 --> 00:16:25.710
I wish to thank the
Radcliffe Institute

00:16:25.710 --> 00:16:30.880
for hosting an event on
the issue of refugees.

00:16:30.880 --> 00:16:34.270
I want to share with you
today from my experience

00:16:34.270 --> 00:16:37.960
of the process of
the preparations

00:16:37.960 --> 00:16:40.310
for the summit that
was held at the United

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:42.920
Nations just a month ago.

00:16:42.920 --> 00:16:44.850
But before that,
to talk a little

00:16:44.850 --> 00:16:46.710
bit about the scope
of the problem.

00:16:46.710 --> 00:16:48.830
I think we've already
had the stage set for us,

00:16:48.830 --> 00:16:53.690
these numbers of 65
million displaced.

00:16:53.690 --> 00:16:55.600
That's a big number.

00:16:55.600 --> 00:17:00.040
As we heard, it's actually now
1% of the world's population.

00:17:00.040 --> 00:17:04.670
65 million is equivalent to
the population of the United

00:17:04.670 --> 00:17:06.869
Kingdom, for example.

00:17:06.869 --> 00:17:08.660
And often, you'll
hear the comparison

00:17:08.660 --> 00:17:12.869
that this is the largest
number of displaced persons

00:17:12.869 --> 00:17:15.180
since the Second World War.

00:17:15.180 --> 00:17:17.560
And I'd like to reflect
on that, because actually,

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:21.550
the population now is three
times greater than what

00:17:21.550 --> 00:17:24.089
it was at the time of
the Second World War.

00:17:24.089 --> 00:17:27.660
And also, the economies of the
rich countries in the world

00:17:27.660 --> 00:17:29.690
have not been devastated.

00:17:29.690 --> 00:17:34.410
So really, this
should be a challenge

00:17:34.410 --> 00:17:36.640
that we can
collectively cope with,

00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:39.290
as well as our
forefathers and mothers

00:17:39.290 --> 00:17:42.470
did after the Second World War.

00:17:42.470 --> 00:17:46.480
Of these 65 million, 21
million are actually refugees,

00:17:46.480 --> 00:17:49.770
meaning that they've crossed
an international border.

00:17:49.770 --> 00:17:52.240
The others are displaced
within their own country,

00:17:52.240 --> 00:17:54.200
including many Syrians
who are displaced

00:17:54.200 --> 00:17:55.770
within their own country.

00:17:55.770 --> 00:17:58.050
And five million Syrians,
or about a quarter

00:17:58.050 --> 00:18:03.560
of the world's refugees,
are displaced from Syria.

00:18:03.560 --> 00:18:05.920
So not only are
the numbers large,

00:18:05.920 --> 00:18:10.430
but the responsibility for
hosting the world's refugees

00:18:10.430 --> 00:18:11.970
is not shared fairly at all.

00:18:11.970 --> 00:18:14.990
When we read the press
or read the newspapers,

00:18:14.990 --> 00:18:16.680
we get the sense
that there are lots

00:18:16.680 --> 00:18:20.920
of refugees coming into
Europe and living in the US.

00:18:20.920 --> 00:18:24.920
But that impression is skewed,
because as we've heard,

00:18:24.920 --> 00:18:27.170
the vast majority of
the world's refugees

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:29.200
are in developing countries.

00:18:29.200 --> 00:18:30.920
In fact, eight
countries in the world,

00:18:30.920 --> 00:18:33.390
all of them in
Africa or Asia, host

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:36.550
half of the world's refugees.

00:18:36.550 --> 00:18:39.048
From their perspective,
this just isn't fair.

00:18:42.340 --> 00:18:44.290
Why do they end up
hosting these refugees?

00:18:44.290 --> 00:18:47.050
Well, it's really an
accident of geography.

00:18:47.050 --> 00:18:49.140
Because of their
proximity to countries

00:18:49.140 --> 00:18:51.150
that are engulfed
in conflict, they

00:18:51.150 --> 00:18:53.760
are the first
responders, and receiving

00:18:53.760 --> 00:18:56.570
large numbers of refugees.

00:18:56.570 --> 00:19:00.020
And they host them
for a very long time.

00:19:00.020 --> 00:19:03.070
Displacement is becoming
more and more protracted.

00:19:03.070 --> 00:19:06.840
Of the 21 million
refugees, how many

00:19:06.840 --> 00:19:09.160
were able to actually
go home last year?

00:19:09.160 --> 00:19:10.270
That's the real success.

00:19:10.270 --> 00:19:12.300
I'm a UNHCR staff
person, I've been

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:14.700
working on refugee
issues for 15 years,

00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:16.360
and the big success
for us is when

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:18.860
refugees can go home
and rebuild their lives.

00:19:18.860 --> 00:19:22.930
But last year, only
200,000 refugees

00:19:22.930 --> 00:19:24.925
were able to return
to their homes.

00:19:27.800 --> 00:19:30.340
And over this last
year, we've seen

00:19:30.340 --> 00:19:35.200
a lack of a coherent response
to these increased numbers.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:38.180
States are reacting
to refugee flows

00:19:38.180 --> 00:19:41.780
with unilateral and highly
restrictive measures.

00:19:41.780 --> 00:19:45.150
They're looking for different
ways to deter entry,

00:19:45.150 --> 00:19:48.990
to restrict rights, to
detain asylum seekers,

00:19:48.990 --> 00:19:53.350
and to put up walls that are
both figurative and literal.

00:19:53.350 --> 00:19:56.490
We see that this causes
immense human suffering,

00:19:56.490 --> 00:19:58.490
that it violates human rights.

00:19:58.490 --> 00:20:04.170
And we also see that it's a
cause of dispute among states.

00:20:04.170 --> 00:20:08.640
And this calls out for an
international solution,

00:20:08.640 --> 00:20:12.970
for multilateral approaches
to solving problems.

00:20:12.970 --> 00:20:15.450
And this became even more
clear in the last year,

00:20:15.450 --> 00:20:19.240
in 2015, which was a
particularly horrible year

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:23.290
for refugees, when we saw people
drowning in the Mediterranean.

00:20:23.290 --> 00:20:25.810
We saw boats adrift
in the Andaman Sea,

00:20:25.810 --> 00:20:29.930
looking for a safe harbor
where people could disembark.

00:20:29.930 --> 00:20:32.990
We saw dangerous land journeys,
not only in the Sahara,

00:20:32.990 --> 00:20:37.260
but closer to our home
here in Central America.

00:20:37.260 --> 00:20:42.090
And then, the rising problems of
protracted displacement, people

00:20:42.090 --> 00:20:45.610
being displaced for 5,
10, 20, even more, years.

00:20:45.610 --> 00:20:47.460
And then, the impact
that all of this

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:51.520
was having on politics,
particularly in Europe, but now

00:20:51.520 --> 00:20:53.960
also in the United
States, where debates

00:20:53.960 --> 00:20:56.800
about resettlement of
Syrians have become

00:20:56.800 --> 00:20:58.110
a matter of national concern.

00:21:00.710 --> 00:21:02.790
Over the past year--
I mean now we're

00:21:02.790 --> 00:21:04.460
coming to the end
of the year, and it

00:21:04.460 --> 00:21:07.240
is a time when we can
start to look back at 2016,

00:21:07.240 --> 00:21:09.710
and reflect on what has
happened so far this year,

00:21:09.710 --> 00:21:12.570
and where things need to go--
there has been an attempt

00:21:12.570 --> 00:21:16.880
to revitalize a multilateral
response to refugee movement.

00:21:16.880 --> 00:21:19.030
So what has happened
over the past year,

00:21:19.030 --> 00:21:22.050
starting in February
of this year,

00:21:22.050 --> 00:21:24.750
there was a major
conference to raise funds

00:21:24.750 --> 00:21:27.360
for the countries that are
supporting Syrian refugees,

00:21:27.360 --> 00:21:31.840
and $12 billion was
pledged at that conference

00:21:31.840 --> 00:21:35.220
for Syrian refugees and the
countries that host them.

00:21:35.220 --> 00:21:38.460
The next month, the
UN refugee agencies

00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:42.130
gathered states to try to
persuade them to increase

00:21:42.130 --> 00:21:45.940
resettlement numbers, so
that more Syrian refugees

00:21:45.940 --> 00:21:49.240
could benefit from resettlement
to third countries.

00:21:49.240 --> 00:21:51.540
The actual results of
that were quite modest,

00:21:51.540 --> 00:21:54.540
but it takes time for countries
to start a program like that,

00:21:54.540 --> 00:21:55.990
a resettlement program.

00:21:55.990 --> 00:21:58.100
And now we're
starting to see, as we

00:21:58.100 --> 00:22:01.950
come to the end of the year,
that more states are pledging

00:22:01.950 --> 00:22:06.080
to start resettlement programs
or to increase their numbers.

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:08.180
Something that many
countries, especially Turkey--

00:22:08.180 --> 00:22:11.190
I know Karim is
working in Turkey--

00:22:11.190 --> 00:22:14.890
are very interested
in seeing increases.

00:22:14.890 --> 00:22:19.130
We had the World Humanitarian
Summit in May of this year

00:22:19.130 --> 00:22:22.370
in Istanbul to try
to improve the way

00:22:22.370 --> 00:22:24.010
that humanitarian
and development

00:22:24.010 --> 00:22:27.360
workers address refugee crises.

00:22:27.360 --> 00:22:29.840
And then, on the
20th of September,

00:22:29.840 --> 00:22:32.690
so the day after the UN
Summit, President Obama

00:22:32.690 --> 00:22:37.770
hosted what was called the
Leaders Summit on Refugees,

00:22:37.770 --> 00:22:40.820
and this brought together
some 52 countries

00:22:40.820 --> 00:22:43.710
that were really ready to make
substantial pledges in terms

00:22:43.710 --> 00:22:46.940
of humanitarian funding,
resettlement places,

00:22:46.940 --> 00:22:52.050
and education and employment
opportunities for refugees.

00:22:52.050 --> 00:22:55.160
So really, there has been
a great deal of attention

00:22:55.160 --> 00:22:58.880
to try to improve a multilateral
response to the Syrian refugee

00:22:58.880 --> 00:22:59.460
crisis.

00:22:59.460 --> 00:23:04.500
But as Jackie has mentioned,
this is not only about Syria.

00:23:04.500 --> 00:23:08.960
And in fact, there can
be negative repercussions

00:23:08.960 --> 00:23:12.300
if we focus only on
one refugee crisis.

00:23:12.300 --> 00:23:15.220
As we were involved in the
intergovernmental negotiations

00:23:15.220 --> 00:23:19.260
leading up to the Summit
on the 19th of September,

00:23:19.260 --> 00:23:20.660
we also heard from
many countries

00:23:20.660 --> 00:23:23.630
that have been hosting
refugees for a very long time,

00:23:23.630 --> 00:23:28.020
and who feel that the
attention to Syrian refugees

00:23:28.020 --> 00:23:31.430
is somehow putting
them at a disadvantage.

00:23:31.430 --> 00:23:35.850
And that can lead to the
squeezing of the protection

00:23:35.850 --> 00:23:39.920
space for refugees
in those countries.

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:44.700
So there is a recognition
that we can't only just keep

00:23:44.700 --> 00:23:48.450
having pledging conferences
and raising money, and maybe

00:23:48.450 --> 00:23:50.000
increasing our
resettlement numbers,

00:23:50.000 --> 00:23:52.830
but we need to think
about longer-term issues

00:23:52.830 --> 00:23:55.370
and global trends.

00:23:55.370 --> 00:23:57.480
And on refugees,
the global trends

00:23:57.480 --> 00:24:02.010
are these permanent shortfalls
in humanitarian funding,

00:24:02.010 --> 00:24:06.510
the length of displacement,
and the disproportionate strain

00:24:06.510 --> 00:24:08.190
on a few countries.

00:24:08.190 --> 00:24:10.730
And then there's also
migration more generally.

00:24:10.730 --> 00:24:14.280
International migration
is a growing global trend,

00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:17.000
but the governance structure
for international migration

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:19.770
is really in its infancy.

00:24:19.770 --> 00:24:22.050
We have better systems
internationally

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:25.400
for governing the movements
of goods and services

00:24:25.400 --> 00:24:29.520
than we do for governing
the movement of people.

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:32.900
And yet, international
migration has traditionally

00:24:32.900 --> 00:24:35.650
been an issue that
member states do not

00:24:35.650 --> 00:24:37.300
want to discuss in
the United Nations,

00:24:37.300 --> 00:24:40.780
because it is considered a
closely guarded attribute

00:24:40.780 --> 00:24:43.790
of national sovereignty, and
not something to be discussed

00:24:43.790 --> 00:24:45.900
in a multilateral forum.

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:48.490
So the goals of
the Summit that we

00:24:48.490 --> 00:24:53.930
held on the 19th of September
at the General Assembly

00:24:53.930 --> 00:24:56.400
was really to
agree on some tools

00:24:56.400 --> 00:25:00.000
for sharing responsibility
for the world's refugees,

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:02.530
and to bring the
issue of migration

00:25:02.530 --> 00:25:05.810
into a multilateral
forum, and to start work

00:25:05.810 --> 00:25:10.510
toward a governance structure
for international migration.

00:25:10.510 --> 00:25:14.420
Now, this Summit occurs in
an intergovernmental context,

00:25:14.420 --> 00:25:16.110
and it occurs in the
General Assembly.

00:25:16.110 --> 00:25:18.320
And that institutional
context is

00:25:18.320 --> 00:25:20.640
important to understand
what actually

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:22.640
happened at the Summit.

00:25:22.640 --> 00:25:25.860
The General Assembly is unique
as an international body,

00:25:25.860 --> 00:25:28.130
in that it brings
together all 193 member

00:25:28.130 --> 00:25:32.580
states with a one-state,
one-vote principle.

00:25:32.580 --> 00:25:34.850
And decisions in
the General Assembly

00:25:34.850 --> 00:25:37.240
are taken by consensus.

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:39.714
That means we try to
get everybody to agree.

00:25:39.714 --> 00:25:41.130
In the last week,
I've been trying

00:25:41.130 --> 00:25:44.690
to get 20 of my colleagues
to agree on a document

00:25:44.690 --> 00:25:46.530
and I've been struggling.

00:25:46.530 --> 00:25:48.770
When you try to do that
in the General Assembly,

00:25:48.770 --> 00:25:53.320
with 193 members states
with very diverse interests,

00:25:53.320 --> 00:25:55.430
it's quite a challenge.

00:25:55.430 --> 00:25:57.420
However, the member
states agreed early on

00:25:57.420 --> 00:25:58.970
in the negotiations
that they didn't

00:25:58.970 --> 00:26:03.300
want to just have the president
of the General Assembly

00:26:03.300 --> 00:26:05.780
write a summary of their
summit and be done with it.

00:26:05.780 --> 00:26:09.300
They actually wanted
to negotiate a text.

00:26:09.300 --> 00:26:12.150
And so we spent
the summer working

00:26:12.150 --> 00:26:14.830
under the leadership of
the ambassadors of Jordan

00:26:14.830 --> 00:26:15.390
and Ireland.

00:26:15.390 --> 00:26:18.250
We spent the summer
trying to negotiate

00:26:18.250 --> 00:26:20.630
this text among states.

00:26:20.630 --> 00:26:23.910
And they really bring very
different perspectives,

00:26:23.910 --> 00:26:29.770
from the states that hosts a
lot of refugees-- I'm trying

00:26:29.770 --> 00:26:30.937
to see how this clock works.

00:26:30.937 --> 00:26:32.186
-You've only got five seconds.

00:26:32.186 --> 00:26:32.990
-Five seconds.

00:26:32.990 --> 00:26:33.724
Oh, dear.

00:26:33.724 --> 00:26:37.850
[LAUGHTER]

00:26:37.850 --> 00:26:41.960
What we ended up with out of
this very difficult negotiation

00:26:41.960 --> 00:26:47.070
was a document that
underlines certain commitments

00:26:47.070 --> 00:26:52.680
to the human rights of
all refugees and migrants,

00:26:52.680 --> 00:26:57.470
reaffirms the 1951
Convention for Refugees.

00:26:57.470 --> 00:27:02.070
It sets up a-- it agrees on a
comprehensive refugee response

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:05.440
plan, and sets forth the
elements for that plan,

00:27:05.440 --> 00:27:08.640
so that we focus not only on
short-term humanitarian needs,

00:27:08.640 --> 00:27:12.590
but longer-term development
needs of countries

00:27:12.590 --> 00:27:14.680
that are hosting refugees.

00:27:14.680 --> 00:27:17.830
And we have a two-year
process to agree

00:27:17.830 --> 00:27:22.120
on what we're calling a Global
Compact on Refugees that

00:27:22.120 --> 00:27:26.330
will establish a fairer system
for sharing responsibility

00:27:26.330 --> 00:27:27.430
among countries.

00:27:27.430 --> 00:27:30.660
We also have a similar process,
an intergovernmental process,

00:27:30.660 --> 00:27:32.860
on migration that
we hope will lead

00:27:32.860 --> 00:27:36.380
to a global compact
for safe, orderly,

00:27:36.380 --> 00:27:40.600
and regular migration by 2018,
and so negotiations on that

00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:44.090
are getting started in New York.

00:27:44.090 --> 00:27:48.420
But I would just end by saying
that that political declaration

00:27:48.420 --> 00:27:52.700
adopted in New York, it
does have a legitimacy,

00:27:52.700 --> 00:27:55.990
it represents a commitment,
but it's not legally binding.

00:27:55.990 --> 00:27:59.610
What it takes to make
the states accountable

00:27:59.610 --> 00:28:02.460
is action on lots
of different levels.

00:28:02.460 --> 00:28:04.040
And I know from
working in the field

00:28:04.040 --> 00:28:07.050
that the most important
action is really

00:28:07.050 --> 00:28:09.750
from the civil
society organizations,

00:28:09.750 --> 00:28:13.300
and from ordinary citizens
who raise these issues, who

00:28:13.300 --> 00:28:19.830
make the situation of refugees
very real, and press for states

00:28:19.830 --> 00:28:24.690
to live up to the commitments
that they made in New York

00:28:24.690 --> 00:28:25.790
on the 19th of September.

00:28:25.790 --> 00:28:26.868
So thank you.

00:28:26.868 --> 00:28:29.358
[APPLAUSE]

00:28:39.320 --> 00:28:40.990
-Thank you all for coming.

00:28:40.990 --> 00:28:43.310
It's quite amazing to
have this number of people

00:28:43.310 --> 00:28:46.070
interested in refugees.

00:28:46.070 --> 00:28:49.210
Those of us who feel like we're
always talking to ourselves

00:28:49.210 --> 00:28:55.120
can be sometimes gratified
by talking to others.

00:28:55.120 --> 00:28:56.800
So I'm going to
move the discussion

00:28:56.800 --> 00:29:01.490
from the more political
orientation to a framework

00:29:01.490 --> 00:29:04.960
of looking at the Syrian crisis
from the point of view of what

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:08.330
the law has to say about it.

00:29:08.330 --> 00:29:12.790
And as you've heard already of
the global refugee total, that

00:29:12.790 --> 00:29:16.550
is convention refugees,
documented now by the United

00:29:16.550 --> 00:29:18.370
Nations High Commissioner
for Refugees,

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:23.990
is 21 million people in 2016.

00:29:23.990 --> 00:29:29.330
Syria represents 22% of
that refugee population.

00:29:29.330 --> 00:29:32.740
It's the largest source
country for refugees

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:35.780
in the world today.

00:29:35.780 --> 00:29:39.230
And as of September
30th, UNHCR figures

00:29:39.230 --> 00:29:44.970
show 4.8 million total
persons from Syria registered

00:29:44.970 --> 00:29:49.400
in the region, 2
million in Turkey alone,

00:29:49.400 --> 00:29:55.060
and the balance of those in
Jordan, Lebanon, Iraq, Egypt,

00:29:55.060 --> 00:29:57.240
and the rest of North Africa.

00:29:57.240 --> 00:30:01.610
Now, these figures have to be
understood in context as well.

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:04.100
Lebanon and Jordan,
along with Syria,

00:30:04.100 --> 00:30:06.760
already hosted the
majority of the world's

00:30:06.760 --> 00:30:10.220
Palestinian refugees
for over 60 years.

00:30:10.220 --> 00:30:13.770
More than 2 million registered
in Jordan, half a million

00:30:13.770 --> 00:30:16.520
in Lebanon, over half
a million in Syria

00:30:16.520 --> 00:30:19.970
before the crisis in 2011.

00:30:19.970 --> 00:30:25.290
Now one person in four
in Lebanon is a refugee.

00:30:25.290 --> 00:30:27.390
While in Jordan, one
of the most water

00:30:27.390 --> 00:30:30.940
stressed countries in the world,
with insufficient capacity

00:30:30.940 --> 00:30:35.850
to provide water and other basic
resources to its own people,

00:30:35.850 --> 00:30:39.880
one quarter of the
population is refugees.

00:30:39.880 --> 00:30:41.810
And that bears some
thinking about when

00:30:41.810 --> 00:30:45.570
we are talking about the numbers
that the United States is

00:30:45.570 --> 00:30:48.896
looking at on its
southern border.

00:30:48.896 --> 00:30:52.490
Despite incredible efforts to
provide for the Syrian refugee

00:30:52.490 --> 00:30:57.310
influx, Jordan and Lebanon have
long since exceeded capacity

00:30:57.310 --> 00:31:01.800
to absorb more refugees, and
both countries quite recently

00:31:01.800 --> 00:31:04.470
closed their borders with Syria.

00:31:04.470 --> 00:31:07.250
What's particularly interesting
from a legal point of view

00:31:07.250 --> 00:31:11.330
is that the main host countries
to the Syrians fleeing the war

00:31:11.330 --> 00:31:15.430
had no applicable refugee and
asylum frameworks in place

00:31:15.430 --> 00:31:17.260
before 2011.

00:31:17.260 --> 00:31:19.590
Lebanon and Jordan
are not parties

00:31:19.590 --> 00:31:22.070
to the main international
treaty governing

00:31:22.070 --> 00:31:25.260
the rights and status of
refugees, the 1951 Refugee

00:31:25.260 --> 00:31:26.720
Convention.

00:31:26.720 --> 00:31:30.520
And although Egypt and Turkey
are parties to the convention,

00:31:30.520 --> 00:31:32.990
they have carved out
significant exceptions

00:31:32.990 --> 00:31:37.220
to its application that have
affected the status of Syrians

00:31:37.220 --> 00:31:39.460
as refugees.

00:31:39.460 --> 00:31:43.220
As a result, all of these
states treated Syrians

00:31:43.220 --> 00:31:46.860
as irregular migrants,
short-term visitors,

00:31:46.860 --> 00:31:49.050
or in other statuses
with policies

00:31:49.050 --> 00:31:51.610
that have fluctuated over time.

00:31:51.610 --> 00:31:54.150
For the first four
years of the crisis,

00:31:54.150 --> 00:31:57.640
these governments did not
conceive of incoming Syrians

00:31:57.640 --> 00:32:00.110
as refugees, per se.

00:32:00.110 --> 00:32:04.210
As guests, migrants, displaced
civilians, or more recently,

00:32:04.210 --> 00:32:07.400
as a result of a major
change in the law in Turkey,

00:32:07.400 --> 00:32:10.630
persons under temporary
protection status.

00:32:10.630 --> 00:32:13.880
As such, even without
formal refugee policies,

00:32:13.880 --> 00:32:17.650
all the frontline states,
until the end of last year,

00:32:17.650 --> 00:32:21.070
were extremely generous in
opening their territories

00:32:21.070 --> 00:32:25.330
to the refugees, establishing
almost open-door policies,

00:32:25.330 --> 00:32:29.240
together hosting the almost
4 million refugees as best

00:32:29.240 --> 00:32:30.630
they could.

00:32:30.630 --> 00:32:32.550
So what changed?

00:32:32.550 --> 00:32:34.560
These basically
open-door policies

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:37.850
towards refugees from
the states in the region

00:32:37.850 --> 00:32:42.480
have become a closed-door policy
towards new Syrian entrance

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:45.290
over the last approximately
year and a half.

00:32:45.290 --> 00:32:47.400
And the key factor
in this change

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:50.500
are the policies imposed
by Western states

00:32:50.500 --> 00:32:55.470
to stem the flood of refugees
from moving beyond the region.

00:32:55.470 --> 00:32:58.520
As Noel discussed,
billions of dollars

00:32:58.520 --> 00:33:01.980
have been raised and spent
already on this crisis.

00:33:01.980 --> 00:33:04.610
As of last September,
Turkey's government

00:33:04.610 --> 00:33:09.680
claimed it had spent
already 5.37 billion euros

00:33:09.680 --> 00:33:14.480
of its own money, well exceeding
the entire donation of the EU

00:33:14.480 --> 00:33:16.450
by then to the crisis.

00:33:16.450 --> 00:33:19.500
But all of the financial
plans, and a host

00:33:19.500 --> 00:33:23.100
of European and Western
policies concerning refugees,

00:33:23.100 --> 00:33:26.350
focus on a paradigm
of containment,

00:33:26.350 --> 00:33:30.980
ensuring the refugee crisis
remains in the region.

00:33:30.980 --> 00:33:33.790
Restrictive policies in
Europe and the Americas,

00:33:33.790 --> 00:33:35.910
including the EU
Schengen and Dublin

00:33:35.910 --> 00:33:39.560
rules, that penalize
illegal border crossers

00:33:39.560 --> 00:33:41.930
and prevent access
to refugee status,

00:33:41.930 --> 00:33:45.330
have created extremely
dangerous barriers

00:33:45.330 --> 00:33:47.500
to Syrian asylum seekers.

00:33:47.500 --> 00:33:51.470
As a result of these barriers,
more than 7,500 people

00:33:51.470 --> 00:33:55.480
have died trying to make
the risky sea crossing

00:33:55.480 --> 00:33:57.820
to Europe since 2014.

00:33:57.820 --> 00:34:00.560
Two children drown
on average every day

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:05.120
in the Mediterranean or
Aegean trying to reach Europe.

00:34:05.120 --> 00:34:08.929
The extremely generous policies
that Turkey, Lebanon, Jordan,

00:34:08.929 --> 00:34:12.610
and even Egypt had put in place
at the start of the crisis

00:34:12.610 --> 00:34:16.060
began rapidly reversing
as a direct result

00:34:16.060 --> 00:34:18.530
of the failure of states
outside the region

00:34:18.530 --> 00:34:23.520
to share responsibility for a
portion of the refugee flow.

00:34:23.520 --> 00:34:26.370
While these countries are
hosting over 4 million

00:34:26.370 --> 00:34:28.679
of the 5 million
Syrian refugees,

00:34:28.679 --> 00:34:31.300
the EU has asked
the European states

00:34:31.300 --> 00:34:37.150
to pledge no more than 160,000
resettlement slots for refugees

00:34:37.150 --> 00:34:40.120
from Syria, Iraq, and Eritrea.

00:34:40.120 --> 00:34:44.989
And so far, no more than
270,000 asylum applications

00:34:44.989 --> 00:34:49.460
have been submitted by
Syrians all across Europe.

00:34:49.460 --> 00:34:53.230
And resettled refugees and
asylum seekers in the EU

00:34:53.230 --> 00:34:58.750
represent far less than 10% of
the Syrian refugee population.

00:34:58.750 --> 00:35:01.000
The US administration's
recent announcement

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:03.820
that it would accept
an additional 10,000

00:35:03.820 --> 00:35:07.180
Syrian refugees this
year, though welcome,

00:35:07.180 --> 00:35:09.900
is also an extremely
small expansion

00:35:09.900 --> 00:35:14.080
to the US's 70,000 yearly
global refugee ceiling,

00:35:14.080 --> 00:35:17.920
and contributes little
to relieving the crisis.

00:35:17.920 --> 00:35:21.330
The latest EU-Turkey agreement
to send refugees back

00:35:21.330 --> 00:35:24.210
who survived the risky
journey by sea or land

00:35:24.210 --> 00:35:26.970
from Turkey to Europe
with a 3 billion

00:35:26.970 --> 00:35:29.950
euro financial incentive
and a, quote unquote,

00:35:29.950 --> 00:35:33.310
"refugee exchange plan",
is only the latest

00:35:33.310 --> 00:35:36.090
of the Western policies
of containment.

00:35:36.090 --> 00:35:40.270
The EU-Turkey agreement, the
combined Dublin-Schengen rules,

00:35:40.270 --> 00:35:43.620
and push-back policies in
the Eastern European states

00:35:43.620 --> 00:35:46.850
are major elements of the
containment paradigm currently

00:35:46.850 --> 00:35:49.810
driving the Middle
East refugee dynamic.

00:35:49.810 --> 00:35:53.460
Meanwhile, major barriers
in US refugee law,

00:35:53.460 --> 00:35:56.180
such as the over-expansive
material support

00:35:56.180 --> 00:35:59.110
for terrorism bars
that prevent thousands

00:35:59.110 --> 00:36:02.730
of legitimate refugees from
being admitted to this country,

00:36:02.730 --> 00:36:04.990
mean that hundreds
of eligible Syrians

00:36:04.990 --> 00:36:09.560
are waiting in limbo after being
granted refugee recognition

00:36:09.560 --> 00:36:12.690
in the host states, while
the multi-agency vetting

00:36:12.690 --> 00:36:17.470
process in the US wends
its way to conclusion.

00:36:17.470 --> 00:36:19.580
The main thrust, then,
of these policies

00:36:19.580 --> 00:36:22.220
is not protection of
the vulnerable migrants

00:36:22.220 --> 00:36:24.990
and refugees who are
the subjects of it,

00:36:24.990 --> 00:36:27.990
but a solidifying of
this containment paradigm

00:36:27.990 --> 00:36:33.410
on which the US and the EU
have operated since the migrant

00:36:33.410 --> 00:36:35.150
and refugee crisis
in the Middle East

00:36:35.150 --> 00:36:37.910
made its way to
Europe and beyond.

00:36:37.910 --> 00:36:40.830
In brief, the
policy's major focus

00:36:40.830 --> 00:36:43.510
is to make sure the refugees
and migrants currently

00:36:43.510 --> 00:36:46.350
hosted in the millions
by the neighboring states

00:36:46.350 --> 00:36:48.880
remain there, and are
barred by whatever

00:36:48.880 --> 00:36:52.180
means necessary from
leaving the region.

00:36:52.180 --> 00:36:54.960
This is exactly the
opposite of the thrust

00:36:54.960 --> 00:36:56.760
of the purpose of
the treaties that

00:36:56.760 --> 00:37:00.910
bind the EU and the wider
community of European and most

00:37:00.910 --> 00:37:02.540
Western states.

00:37:02.540 --> 00:37:04.900
The primary and, of
course, most important

00:37:04.900 --> 00:37:08.040
international legal
obligations towards refugees

00:37:08.040 --> 00:37:11.080
arise from the 1951
Refugee Convention

00:37:11.080 --> 00:37:14.900
and its companion
1967 Protocol, as one

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:17.390
or both of these
instruments bind

00:37:17.390 --> 00:37:21.830
all the states in Europe,
the US, as well as Turkey.

00:37:21.830 --> 00:37:24.270
The essential elements
of the Refugee Convention

00:37:24.270 --> 00:37:27.900
are the obligation not to
return a refugee to a place

00:37:27.900 --> 00:37:31.630
where she risks persecution,
non-refoulement,

00:37:31.630 --> 00:37:34.050
the obligation of
each state party

00:37:34.050 --> 00:37:37.710
to provide fair access
to asylum procedures

00:37:37.710 --> 00:37:41.320
to refugees on a
nondiscriminatory basis,

00:37:41.320 --> 00:37:44.810
and the prohibition against
collective expulsion.

00:37:44.810 --> 00:37:47.000
These elements
are expanded under

00:37:47.000 --> 00:37:49.740
European regional
instruments, such as the EU

00:37:49.740 --> 00:37:52.660
Charter, the Civil and
Political Rights Treaty,

00:37:52.660 --> 00:37:54.820
the European Convention
on Human Rights,

00:37:54.820 --> 00:37:58.620
and decisions of the two
European courts, the Strasbourg

00:37:58.620 --> 00:38:01.250
and the Luxembourg courts.

00:38:01.250 --> 00:38:03.620
These courts have
further articulated

00:38:03.620 --> 00:38:07.610
that collective expulsion
includes when a state removes

00:38:07.610 --> 00:38:11.360
refugees and migrants from its
territory in any manner that

00:38:11.360 --> 00:38:15.400
fails to provide them with
access to fair procedures

00:38:15.400 --> 00:38:17.580
for international protection.

00:38:17.580 --> 00:38:20.010
The prohibition against
collective expulsion

00:38:20.010 --> 00:38:23.130
also includes removing
persons on the basis

00:38:23.130 --> 00:38:25.930
of their national
or ethnic identity,

00:38:25.930 --> 00:38:30.340
through pro forma proceedings,
or without access to counsel,

00:38:30.340 --> 00:38:34.660
or where not appeal is available
from a removal decision.

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:38.640
Focusing further on Europe,
under EU laws and regulations,

00:38:38.640 --> 00:38:41.720
there are additional
obligations on member states.

00:38:41.720 --> 00:38:44.130
In situations of
emergency, where

00:38:44.130 --> 00:38:47.320
there is mass influx
of displaced persons,

00:38:47.320 --> 00:38:51.500
EU states must provide temporary
protection against return,

00:38:51.500 --> 00:38:53.800
regardless of internal
EU arrangements

00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:58.680
such as Dublin and
Schengen. European states

00:38:58.680 --> 00:39:00.670
parties to the
European Convention

00:39:00.670 --> 00:39:03.830
are prohibited from sending
refugees to other states

00:39:03.830 --> 00:39:06.300
where the individuals
would be at risk of return

00:39:06.300 --> 00:39:10.680
to persecution or violations
of their convention rights.

00:39:10.680 --> 00:39:13.660
It is well accepted that
international responsibility

00:39:13.660 --> 00:39:16.900
and burden sharing
of refugees is today

00:39:16.900 --> 00:39:19.960
a legal obligation
on all states parties

00:39:19.960 --> 00:39:21.870
to the Refugee Convention.

00:39:21.870 --> 00:39:25.580
In spite of all this, the
way forward is well-known.

00:39:25.580 --> 00:39:27.680
Under prior
international practice,

00:39:27.680 --> 00:39:30.920
all states parties to the
Refugee Convention regime,

00:39:30.920 --> 00:39:34.220
not just European states,
should be participating

00:39:34.220 --> 00:39:38.640
in a UNHCR-led proposal for a
comprehensive plan of action

00:39:38.640 --> 00:39:41.030
that sets out
numbers of refugees

00:39:41.030 --> 00:39:43.330
that each state
agrees to accept,

00:39:43.330 --> 00:39:46.910
the various kinds of status
that participating states are

00:39:46.910 --> 00:39:50.090
willing to provide, minimum
standards of benefits

00:39:50.090 --> 00:39:53.550
to be granted the refugees,
and fair refugee status

00:39:53.550 --> 00:39:56.780
determinations in all states.

00:39:56.780 --> 00:40:00.450
Such CPAs have been negotiated
in mass refugee flows

00:40:00.450 --> 00:40:03.760
all over the world
from the 1970s onwards,

00:40:03.760 --> 00:40:06.350
and well established
guidelines and criteria

00:40:06.350 --> 00:40:11.640
exist as solid precedent to
resolve this current crisis.

00:40:11.640 --> 00:40:14.280
These are legal
obligations, and are the key

00:40:14.280 --> 00:40:17.670
to providing a real and durable
solution to the millions

00:40:17.670 --> 00:40:20.480
of individual human
beings forced from home

00:40:20.480 --> 00:40:23.950
and victimized by a crisis
not of their making.

00:40:23.950 --> 00:40:26.222
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:36.200 --> 00:40:38.780
-Thank you all for
showing interest.

00:40:38.780 --> 00:40:40.720
And thank you for
Radcliffe Institute

00:40:40.720 --> 00:40:44.300
for giving this
platform to try to build

00:40:44.300 --> 00:40:49.070
a common understanding of the
cause of this refugee crisis.

00:40:49.070 --> 00:40:52.330
Whenever I'm invited
to talk about Syria,

00:40:52.330 --> 00:40:55.200
I set to prepare
some talking points,

00:40:55.200 --> 00:40:58.570
but within minutes the
nostalgia takes me there,

00:40:58.570 --> 00:41:02.750
where I miss my room, I
miss my library, my diary,

00:41:02.750 --> 00:41:04.960
which should be sitting
somewhere under that rubble

00:41:04.960 --> 00:41:07.050
now.

00:41:07.050 --> 00:41:11.460
Each single family in Syria
has lost either a family member

00:41:11.460 --> 00:41:13.530
or a house or belongings.

00:41:13.530 --> 00:41:19.000
Syria has lost-- 700,000 people
were killed out of 23 million

00:41:19.000 --> 00:41:22.470
of their population, which means
each single family, especially

00:41:22.470 --> 00:41:24.360
in the
opposition-controlled areas,

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:27.570
they lost a family member.

00:41:27.570 --> 00:41:29.530
However, as I have
just 10 minutes,

00:41:29.530 --> 00:41:32.700
I will try to go
as fast as I can.

00:41:32.700 --> 00:41:38.310
And bear with me if
I wasn't very fast.

00:41:38.310 --> 00:41:41.680
So why now are we talking
about this refugee crisis?

00:41:41.680 --> 00:41:44.270
Why now, starting from 2015?

00:41:44.270 --> 00:41:47.480
The answer is obvious,
because some refugees

00:41:47.480 --> 00:41:49.680
arrived to Europe.

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:53.480
These refugees started
in 2012 and 2013.

00:41:53.480 --> 00:41:56.800
Syrians were daily
fleeing out of country,

00:41:56.800 --> 00:42:00.340
and we heard the numbers
from Susan and Noel

00:42:00.340 --> 00:42:02.520
about the numbers in the region.

00:42:05.961 --> 00:42:08.210
But the problem is that some
countries or some people,

00:42:08.210 --> 00:42:10.440
maybe, they don't feel
the suffering or the pain

00:42:10.440 --> 00:42:14.230
until the risk
knocks at their door.

00:42:14.230 --> 00:42:15.540
It is a long trip.

00:42:15.540 --> 00:42:17.220
It is a long, risky trip.

00:42:17.220 --> 00:42:23.510
So Syrians, they go from Syria
through the Turkish border.

00:42:23.510 --> 00:42:25.510
Which could be
risky, because Turkey

00:42:25.510 --> 00:42:29.160
has closed their
border since 2015,

00:42:29.160 --> 00:42:33.260
and most families and persons,
they are crossing illegally.

00:42:33.260 --> 00:42:36.880
Just in July, a few months
ago, a family was crossing.

00:42:36.880 --> 00:42:41.470
Of 15 family members, 11 of them
were killed by the Turkish army

00:42:41.470 --> 00:42:45.390
while they were trying to
cross illegally to Turkey.

00:42:45.390 --> 00:42:47.930
And then, from Turkey
to Greece, crossing

00:42:47.930 --> 00:42:50.890
the sea, which is
the most risky part.

00:42:50.890 --> 00:42:53.220
And then, there are
a lot of barriers

00:42:53.220 --> 00:42:57.480
here until they arrived to
their final destinations.

00:42:57.480 --> 00:43:02.490
And we saw a lot of photos of
families drowning in the sea.

00:43:02.490 --> 00:43:08.470
2,500 people drowned in the
Mediterranean in this crisis.

00:43:08.470 --> 00:43:10.860
And we should ask
ourselves why it

00:43:10.860 --> 00:43:14.090
seems that the conditions
they are escaping from

00:43:14.090 --> 00:43:18.040
are worse than
drowning in the sea.

00:43:18.040 --> 00:43:21.480
And it's not just the
only displacement.

00:43:21.480 --> 00:43:23.950
There are other displacements.

00:43:23.950 --> 00:43:25.880
Could be even more in numbers.

00:43:25.880 --> 00:43:27.470
The internal
displacement, people

00:43:27.470 --> 00:43:31.460
in Syria on a daily
basis, on a weekly basis,

00:43:31.460 --> 00:43:33.770
we have massive population
movements escaping

00:43:33.770 --> 00:43:35.950
from violence within Syria.

00:43:35.950 --> 00:43:40.160
We have a lot of ad hoc camps
next to the Turkish border,

00:43:40.160 --> 00:43:42.310
and everywhere in Syria,
containing at least

00:43:42.310 --> 00:43:44.290
300,000 people or more.

00:43:44.290 --> 00:43:48.010
These camps are
completely not organized,

00:43:48.010 --> 00:43:50.510
because there is no
official presence

00:43:50.510 --> 00:43:53.010
of the UNHCR or
international organizations

00:43:53.010 --> 00:43:54.650
to organize these camps.

00:43:54.650 --> 00:43:56.760
So it has the
minimum-- does not even

00:43:56.760 --> 00:44:00.500
have the minimum level
of shelter conditions.

00:44:00.500 --> 00:44:02.900
Most of these families
are women and children.

00:44:02.900 --> 00:44:05.720
Some families, they had
to move several times

00:44:05.720 --> 00:44:08.310
until they arrived to
their final destination.

00:44:08.310 --> 00:44:12.300
This family we met in Idlib,
they moved four times,

00:44:12.300 --> 00:44:15.320
from Damascus to rural Damascus,
and then to Homs, and then

00:44:15.320 --> 00:44:18.405
to northern Hama, until
they arrived to this school

00:44:18.405 --> 00:44:20.970
in Idlib, where they are
sharing the classroom

00:44:20.970 --> 00:44:22.540
with other families.

00:44:22.540 --> 00:44:25.970
But look at her
having some hope,

00:44:25.970 --> 00:44:30.160
looking into her child's eyes.

00:44:30.160 --> 00:44:32.110
The question is, why?

00:44:32.110 --> 00:44:35.250
And the reason is obvious,
because of the Syrian crisis.

00:44:35.250 --> 00:44:39.000
But could we define
what's happening in Syria?

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:43.320
It is a civil war or
a public revolution?

00:44:43.320 --> 00:44:44.620
We have a lot of answers.

00:44:44.620 --> 00:44:47.370
We don't have at the moment
a common understanding

00:44:47.370 --> 00:44:50.090
of what's happening in Syria.

00:44:50.090 --> 00:44:53.300
And maybe because of
the media, maybe because

00:44:53.300 --> 00:44:57.120
of the political complications.

00:44:57.120 --> 00:44:59.590
I will try as best
as I can to build

00:44:59.590 --> 00:45:06.530
a common understanding quickly,
an intro one, as much as I can.

00:45:06.530 --> 00:45:08.890
This map is for Syria currently.

00:45:08.890 --> 00:45:13.960
Each color refers to a different
party, and within each color

00:45:13.960 --> 00:45:18.170
there are different sub-parties
or different groups.

00:45:18.170 --> 00:45:22.800
The red one is the regime where
they control the main cities.

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:25.880
The green one is the
opposition's, and there

00:45:25.880 --> 00:45:28.910
are hundreds of fractions.

00:45:28.910 --> 00:45:33.390
The black one is ISIL and
the yellow one is the Kurds.

00:45:33.390 --> 00:45:36.090
And here, the blue one
here, is the Turks,

00:45:36.090 --> 00:45:40.640
because even the Turks
now are in Syria.

00:45:40.640 --> 00:45:43.890
To understand maybe
the crisis is quickly,

00:45:43.890 --> 00:45:46.480
to review the timeline
of this crisis,

00:45:46.480 --> 00:45:50.480
the spark started
in March 2011, when

00:45:50.480 --> 00:45:53.550
some children from Talkalakh,
they wrote some statements

00:45:53.550 --> 00:45:57.290
against the regime on the wall,
and the children were punished

00:45:57.290 --> 00:45:59.760
by the intelligence agencies.

00:45:59.760 --> 00:46:03.230
People went into
demonstrations against this,

00:46:03.230 --> 00:46:05.810
and these demonstrations
spread out of the country.

00:46:05.810 --> 00:46:07.610
This photo is from Hama.

00:46:07.610 --> 00:46:11.620
But the response from
the intelligence agencies

00:46:11.620 --> 00:46:15.620
against these protesters
was really violent,

00:46:15.620 --> 00:46:18.320
so that's why some
commanders and soldiers

00:46:18.320 --> 00:46:19.910
from the Syrian
Army, they refused

00:46:19.910 --> 00:46:21.460
to participate in
these practices

00:46:21.460 --> 00:46:23.930
against the protesters.

00:46:23.930 --> 00:46:26.420
So they established
in 2011 something

00:46:26.420 --> 00:46:29.430
called the Free Syrian Army.

00:46:29.430 --> 00:46:32.950
In 2013, the Free Syrian
Army expanded and controlled

00:46:32.950 --> 00:46:35.650
a lot of rural areas.

00:46:35.650 --> 00:46:40.070
But the regime, they are still
controlling the main capitals.

00:46:40.070 --> 00:46:43.400
And the Kurds, they have
some process in their areas.

00:46:43.400 --> 00:46:48.130
In 2014, the situation
came to be complicated,

00:46:48.130 --> 00:46:50.630
because there were a
lot of parties involved

00:46:50.630 --> 00:46:53.090
from the regime side,
mainly Hezbollah

00:46:53.090 --> 00:46:59.630
from Lebanon, some Shia
militias from Iraq and Iran.

00:46:59.630 --> 00:47:02.760
And again, the Turkish
border from the other side,

00:47:02.760 --> 00:47:05.680
the opposition's, brought
a lot of jihadists

00:47:05.680 --> 00:47:10.440
to fight, because the war
starting from this point

00:47:10.440 --> 00:47:13.540
maybe had some
sectorial perspectives,

00:47:13.540 --> 00:47:19.670
because some of the parties
participated in this conflict.

00:47:19.670 --> 00:47:24.110
And here we have in 2014
the first presence of ISIL,

00:47:24.110 --> 00:47:25.930
but in limited areas.

00:47:25.930 --> 00:47:30.200
In 2015, ISIL has
expanded a lot.

00:47:30.200 --> 00:47:33.200
50% of Syria was
controlled by ISIL.

00:47:33.200 --> 00:47:36.670
The regime shrank
to the main cities,

00:47:36.670 --> 00:47:39.530
and the opposition's,
maybe they selected

00:47:39.530 --> 00:47:43.380
or they were given
Idlib as the main hub.

00:47:43.380 --> 00:47:48.100
And the Kurds, they
are in the same areas.

00:47:48.100 --> 00:47:53.790
In 2016, here you go, we
have more external parties.

00:47:53.790 --> 00:47:58.390
We have Russia, they have boots
on the ground with the regime,

00:47:58.390 --> 00:48:01.340
Iran sent boots on the
ground, in addition to

00:48:01.340 --> 00:48:04.170
Hezbollah and Iraqi militias.

00:48:04.170 --> 00:48:07.510
And from the other
side, the US with

00:48:07.510 --> 00:48:12.220
an international collation,
they hit areas in ISIS.

00:48:12.220 --> 00:48:14.140
The US, they support
the Kurds, and they

00:48:14.140 --> 00:48:15.980
are fighting against ISIS.

00:48:15.980 --> 00:48:19.380
So that's why Kurds, they
expanded a little bit.

00:48:19.380 --> 00:48:24.970
But because of the tension
between Turkey and the Kurds,

00:48:24.970 --> 00:48:27.870
the Turks expanded to
have some lands here.

00:48:27.870 --> 00:48:29.990
And there are many
other parties.

00:48:29.990 --> 00:48:31.970
Maybe they don't have
boots on the ground,

00:48:31.970 --> 00:48:33.960
but they are still
involved in this crisis.

00:48:33.960 --> 00:48:39.320
So it is not a
Syrian-to-Syrian conflict.

00:48:39.320 --> 00:48:42.320
Just recently,
Aleppo City, which

00:48:42.320 --> 00:48:45.890
is the second-largest
city in Syria,

00:48:45.890 --> 00:48:48.110
was completely
besieged by the regime,

00:48:48.110 --> 00:48:51.230
putting approximately
300,000 people

00:48:51.230 --> 00:48:53.310
under besiegement in this area.

00:48:53.310 --> 00:48:56.380
They don't have any access
to any life services.

00:48:56.380 --> 00:49:00.870
Just quickly, I will say quick
statements, and if it's true,

00:49:00.870 --> 00:49:02.670
raise your hand, please, OK?

00:49:02.670 --> 00:49:04.640
About the besieged areas.

00:49:04.640 --> 00:49:07.000
The regime allows injured
people and medical cases

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:09.970
to get out of the besieged
area seeking medical help.

00:49:09.970 --> 00:49:11.580
Is it true?

00:49:11.580 --> 00:49:12.790
No, it is not true.

00:49:12.790 --> 00:49:16.130
A lot of people, they die
in the besieged areas,

00:49:16.130 --> 00:49:18.490
because they cannot
seek medical help.

00:49:18.490 --> 00:49:24.050
Food, water, fuel are not
allowed to get in at any point.

00:49:24.050 --> 00:49:26.550
It is true.

00:49:26.550 --> 00:49:29.183
Medical supplies are excluded
from the restrictions.

00:49:32.290 --> 00:49:35.090
No, it is not excluded,
even medical supplies.

00:49:35.090 --> 00:49:37.245
The hospitals now, they
are suffering, especially

00:49:37.245 --> 00:49:40.570
in Aleppo, from having
no medical supplies.

00:49:40.570 --> 00:49:42.820
Aid workers and UN
agencies are allowed

00:49:42.820 --> 00:49:44.360
to enter besieged
areas, but they

00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:46.747
don't want to enter,
ensuring their staff safety.

00:49:49.562 --> 00:49:51.020
Seems you have a
good understanding

00:49:51.020 --> 00:49:53.570
about the besieged areas.

00:49:53.570 --> 00:49:54.960
It is not true.

00:49:54.960 --> 00:50:00.530
They are not allowed to
enter the besieged areas.

00:50:00.530 --> 00:50:01.980
It's not just the besiegement.

00:50:01.980 --> 00:50:05.230
There are daily targetings
of civilian infrastructure.

00:50:05.230 --> 00:50:07.540
Just in July and
August, the health class

00:50:07.540 --> 00:50:10.870
reported more than
30 hospitals being

00:50:10.870 --> 00:50:14.750
destroyed, either partially or
completely, by the air strikes.

00:50:14.750 --> 00:50:19.370
Just in one night, the 24th
of July, five hospitals out

00:50:19.370 --> 00:50:23.660
of the 10 functioning hospitals
in Aleppo were destroyed.

00:50:23.660 --> 00:50:27.135
And just to imagine
yourself in this hospital,

00:50:27.135 --> 00:50:33.600
quickly, this is one
hospital in Aleppo.

00:50:33.600 --> 00:50:36.700
So while the patients
are getting treatment,

00:50:36.700 --> 00:50:38.340
the hospital is being targeted.

00:50:38.340 --> 00:50:42.570
And this hospital was targeted
three times in July just,

00:50:42.570 --> 00:50:44.803
and this hospital went
out of service completely.

00:50:48.640 --> 00:50:50.640
Just quickly, because
we're running out of time,

00:50:50.640 --> 00:50:52.800
education is the same story.

00:50:52.800 --> 00:50:55.950
This hospital is our Safe
Children support Hospital

00:50:55.950 --> 00:50:56.940
in [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:56.940 --> 00:50:58.990
It was targeted three times.

00:50:58.990 --> 00:51:02.490
Each time we
rehabilitated the school,

00:51:02.490 --> 00:51:05.950
and the school was
targeted again and again.

00:51:05.950 --> 00:51:08.510
So why do people
flee out of Syria?

00:51:08.510 --> 00:51:10.040
My opinion is three reasons.

00:51:10.040 --> 00:51:12.130
Violence, which we talked about.

00:51:12.130 --> 00:51:13.580
Basic life services--
if you don't

00:51:13.580 --> 00:51:18.300
have water, food, medical help,
for sure, you will not stay.

00:51:18.300 --> 00:51:20.770
And personal documentation,
which is an interesting one.

00:51:20.770 --> 00:51:22.650
Because people in
the opposition areas,

00:51:22.650 --> 00:51:24.470
they don't have access
to the government

00:51:24.470 --> 00:51:26.430
and they don't have
any representation.

00:51:26.430 --> 00:51:29.580
So they cannot get
birth registrations,

00:51:29.580 --> 00:51:31.210
death registrations,
or passports.

00:51:31.210 --> 00:51:34.130
So they seek asylum
to have documents

00:51:34.130 --> 00:51:36.380
showing their identity.

00:51:36.380 --> 00:51:40.050
And then, solutions.

00:51:40.050 --> 00:51:44.130
Is the solution by asking
countries to absorb more?

00:51:44.130 --> 00:51:45.950
I hope it's just the
temporary solution,

00:51:45.950 --> 00:51:49.360
because Syria is losing their
people, doctors, teachers,

00:51:49.360 --> 00:51:51.740
who are supposed to
build the country again.

00:51:51.740 --> 00:51:53.520
We were able to do
a lot, and we are

00:51:53.520 --> 00:51:56.790
able to do a lot in Syria--
vaccination hospitals,

00:51:56.790 --> 00:52:00.520
schools, even without
electricity, around candles,

00:52:00.520 --> 00:52:06.200
and some spaces among the
violence for children to play.

00:52:06.200 --> 00:52:11.750
But we were not able to fund all
our humanitarian response plan,

00:52:11.750 --> 00:52:15.480
and we do have to
have a lot of advocacy

00:52:15.480 --> 00:52:17.490
to build this
common understanding

00:52:17.490 --> 00:52:18.630
of the Syrian crisis.

00:52:18.630 --> 00:52:21.130
And finally, to strengthen
Syrian civil society,

00:52:21.130 --> 00:52:24.120
because it is the
best way to-- having

00:52:24.120 --> 00:52:25.940
the structure of
this community again,

00:52:25.940 --> 00:52:28.840
hopefully, again
later will be a merge

00:52:28.840 --> 00:52:30.900
between the civil society
in the regime area

00:52:30.900 --> 00:52:33.260
and the civil society
in the opposition area.

00:52:33.260 --> 00:52:37.940
And we had many good
examples of associations

00:52:37.940 --> 00:52:41.140
where we are able to establish
this Idlib [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:41.140 --> 00:52:44.650
and Idlib Governorate managing
all these health centers,

00:52:44.650 --> 00:52:48.460
and a lot of Syrian
NGOs managing up to 23

00:52:48.460 --> 00:52:50.770
million operations in Syria.

00:52:50.770 --> 00:52:51.600
Thank you.

00:52:51.600 --> 00:52:54.050
[APPLAUSE]

